#Text=Rowland York
#Text=Rowland York or Yorke ( died 1588 ) was an English soldier of fortune and defector to Spain .
#Text=Early life
#Text=Rowland York was the ninth of eleven sons of Sir John York . [ 1 ] [ 2 ]
#Text=He volunteered for the Netherlands under Thomas Morgan of Llantarnam in 1572 .

#Text=He embarked at Gravesend on 19 March that year with his two companions , the poet George Gascoigne and William Herle , but the ship in which they sailed was nearly lost on the coast of Holland owing to the incompetence of the Dutch pilot . [ 3 ]

#Text=Reaching the English camp in safety , he took part in August that year in the attack on Goes under Captain ( afterwards Sir ) Humphrey Gilbert and the Prince of Orange 's agent Jerome Tseraerts . [ 4 ]
#Text=Plots and equivocal reputation
#Text=Opinions differed about York .
#Text=By some he was held " bolde of courage , provident in direction , industrious in labour , and quick in execution " . [ 5 ]
#Text=But his profligacy and the fact that he was a Roman Catholic caused him from the first to be distrusted by the states . [ 6 ]
#Text=In October 1580 he was reported by William Herle to Francis Walsingham to have been arrested on a charge of felony . [ 7 ]
#Text=Four years later York was detected in a plot with John Van Imbyss to betray Ghent to the Duke of Parma . [ 8 ]

#Text=Against the advice of the Prince of Orange , who would have preferred a more summary punishment , he was clapped in prison in Brussels , whence he was released when the city fell into Parma 's hands in 1585 .
#Text=He served at the siege of Antwerp , but by the intercession of his friends he was allowed to return to England .
#Text=Joining the expedition under the Earl of Leicester that year , he succeeded in ingratiating himself with Sir Philip Sidney . [ 6 ]

#Text=Appointed by Leicester to the command of the Zutphen sconce , he , according to William Camden , took the opportunity thus offered him of paying back a grudge he had against the earl by surrendering the sconce to the Spaniards and inducing Sir William Stanley to do the same for Deventer .
#Text=He was appointed captain of a troop of lancers in the Spanish service ; but was not , as he thought , sufficiently rewarded .
#Text=Since he was known to be a bold and determined villain , [ 9 ] it is said the Spaniards took precaution to prevent any double treachery by causing him to be poisoned .
#Text=Death
#Text=He died on a Sunday in February 1588 , having first ‘ received sacraments , unction , and all ’ . [ 10 ]
#Text=Three years later his body was exhumed and gibbeted by order of the states .
#Text=His heir was Edmund Yorke , who was executed at Tyburn in 1595 for attempting to assassinate Queen Elizabeth .

#Text=Edmund had been persuaded by his uncle 's associate Sir William Stanley , and Stanley 's rather mysterious lieutenant Jacques de Francesci ( Captain Jacques ) , that the assassination would be a meritorious act .
#Text=On returning to England he quickly fell under suspicion , due perhaps to his association with the Irish fencing master Patrick O'Collun .
#Text=They were both arrested , along with Richard Williams , and all three were convicted of treason and executed .
